hands_on_practices.solution:
We begin with the classical thin plate theory for an isotropic material. The constitutive relation linking bending moments to curvatures introduces the bending rigidity (also called bending stiffness) per unit width, denoted $B$. For an isotropic linear elastic plate of thickness $t$, Young’s modulus $E$, and Poisson’s ratio $\nu$, the bending rigidity is
$$
B \;=\; \frac{E\,t^{3}}{12\left(1-\nu^{2}\right)}.
$$
This follows from integrating the linear elastic stress distribution through the thickness under pure bending and relating the resultant moment to curvature.

Next, we define the elastocapillary length $L_{ec}$ by balancing capillary energy and bending energy at a characteristic lateral scale. The capillary energy over an area of order $L^{2}$ is
$$
U_{\text{cap}} \sim \gamma\,L^{2}.
$$
For a shape with curvature of order $\kappa\sim 1/L$, the bending energy density is of order $B\,\kappa^{2}$, hence the bending energy over area $L^{2}$ scales as
$$
U_{\text{bend}} \sim B\,\kappa^{2}\,L^{2} \sim B\,\frac{1}{L^{2}}\,L^{2} \sim B.
$$
The elastocapillary length $L_{ec}$ is the scale at which these two energies are comparable:
$$
U_{\text{cap}} \sim U_{\text{bend}} \quad \Longrightarrow \quad \gamma\,L_{ec}^{2} \sim B \quad \Longrightarrow \quad L_{ec} \;=\; \sqrt{\frac{B}{\gamma}}.
$$

We now define the elastocapillary number $\mathrm{Ec}$ as the ratio of capillary energy to bending energy at the given scale $L$:
$$
\mathrm{Ec} \;\equiv\; \frac{U_{\text{cap}}}{U_{\text{bend}}} \;\sim\; \frac{\gamma\,L^{2}}{B}.
$$
Equivalently, using $L_{ec}^{2}=B/\gamma$, one may write $\mathrm{Ec}=(L/L_{ec})^{2}$, which is a common dimensionless measure of capillarity versus elasticity at the scale $L$.

We now compute the requested quantities using the provided data, working symbolically until the final numerical substitution:

Given $E=1\ \mathrm{GPa}=1.00\times 10^{9}\ \mathrm{Pa}$, $t=100\ \mathrm{nm}=1.00\times 10^{-7}\ \mathrm{m}$, $\nu=0.3$, and $\gamma=0.07\ \mathrm{N/m}$:
1) Bending rigidity:
$$
B \;=\; \frac{E\,t^{3}}{12\left(1-\nu^{2}\right)}
\;=\;
\frac{\left(1.00\times 10^{9}\right)\left(1.00\times 10^{-7}\right)^{3}}{12\left(1-0.3^{2}\right)}
\;=\;
\frac{1.00\times 10^{-12}}{12\cdot 0.91}
\;=\;
\frac{1.00\times 10^{-12}}{10.92}
\;\approx\;
9.157509\times 10^{-14}.
$$
Thus, to three significant figures,
$$
B \;\approx\; 9.16\times 10^{-14}\ \mathrm{N\cdot m}.
$$

2) Elastocapillary length:
$$
L_{ec} \;=\; \sqrt{\frac{B}{\gamma}}
\;=\;
\sqrt{\frac{1.00\times 10^{-12}/10.92}{0.07}}
\;=\;
\sqrt{\frac{1.00\times 10^{-12}}{0.7644}}
\;=\;
\sqrt{1.30856\times 10^{-12}}
\;=\;
\left(\sqrt{1.30856}\right)\times 10^{-6}
\;\approx\;
1.144\times 10^{-6}\ \mathrm{m}.
$$
Expressed in micrometers,
$$
L_{ec} \;\approx\; 1.14\ \mu\mathrm{m}
$$
to three significant figures.

3) Elastocapillary number at $L=10\ \mu\mathrm{m}=1.00\times 10^{-5}\ \mathrm{m}$:
$$
\mathrm{Ec} \;=\; \frac{\gamma\,L^{2}}{B}
\;=\;
\frac{0.07\;\times\;\left(1.00\times 10^{-5}\right)^{2}}{9.157509\times 10^{-14}}
\;=\;
\frac{0.07\times 1.00\times 10^{-10}}{9.157509\times 10^{-14}}
\;=\;
\frac{7.00\times 10^{-12}}{9.157509\times 10^{-14}}
\;\approx\;
76.44.
$$
Equivalently, using $\mathrm{Ec}=(L/L_{ec})^{2}$ gives the same value within rounding. To three significant figures,
$$
\mathrm{Ec} \;\approx\; 76.4.
$$

Collecting the results in the requested order $(B, L_{ec}, \mathrm{Ec})$, rounded to three significant figures and with the specified units:
- $B \approx 9.16\times 10^{-14}\ \mathrm{N\cdot m}$,
- $L_{ec} \approx 1.14\ \mu\mathrm{m}$,
- $\mathrm{Ec} \approx 76.4$ (dimensionless).
